uiEntry.title: map_overlay

uiEntry.title: map
uiEntry.tooltip: Taxes map||This shows how your current tax rate is affecting your population's public order.||Green provinces show a population under control, yellow means they are neutral and red means they are unhappy and could revolt.||You can adjust the tax rate with the tax slider below, and the map will update to show the effects.

uiEntry.title: header_box
uiEntry.tooltip: All your incomings and outgoings are detailed here.||The total income for the next turn is totalled at the bottom of this panel.||Move your cursor over the details below for more information.

uiEntry.title: tx_income
uiEntry.tooltip: Income gained from taxing the wealth of all your provinces.||This number is based on your current tax rate.||If you change the tax rate before the next turn this will change accordingly.

uiEntry.title: dy_tax-income
uiEntry.tooltip: Income gained from taxing the wealth of all your provinces.||This number is based on your current tax rate.||If you change the tax rate before the next turn this will change accordingly.

uiEntry.title: tx_trade
uiEntry.tooltip: Income gained from exporting your clan's resources to your trade partners via trade routes as well as internal trade of unsold goods.||Throughout your provinces you will have trade resources and these are shipped in to your provincial capital.||If the trade supply exceeds the demand, the surplus is exported through trade routes to your trade partners.||To increase this income, develop trade resources and make more trade partners.||You can see a breakdown of your supply and exports in the trade tab of this panel.

uiEntry.title: dy_trade
uiEntry.tooltip: Income gained from exporting your clan's resources to your trade partners via trade routes.||Throughout your provinces you will have trade resources and these are shipped in to your provincial capital.||If the trade supply exceeds the demand, the surplus is exported through trade routes to your trade partners.||To increase this income, develop trade resources and make more trade partners.||You can see a breakdown of your supply and exports in the trade tab of this panel.

uiEntry.title: tx_other
uiEntry.tooltip: Income gained from other sources such as payments from diplomatic negotiations and any vassal clans.

uiEntry.title: dy_other
uiEntry.tooltip: Income gained from other sources such as payments from diplomatic negotiations and any vassal clans.

uiEntry.title: tx_upkeep_army
uiEntry.tooltip: Amount of money per turn to support your armies.||Disband units to reduce this figure.||Armies are made up of units.||Each unit has an upkeep cost in its unit details panel.||Units that are not doing anything are simply wasting money.||Disband them or move them where they are needed.

uiEntry.title: dy_army-upkeep
uiEntry.tooltip: Amount of money per turn to support your armies.||Disband units to reduce this figure.||Armies are made up of units.||Each unit has an upkeep cost in its unit details panel.||Units that are not doing anything are simply wasting money.||Disband them or move them where they are needed.

uiEntry.title: tx_upkeep_navy
uiEntry.tooltip: Amount of money per turn to support your fleets.||Disband ships to reduce this figure.||Fleets are made up of ships.||Each ship has an upkeep cost in its ship details panel.||Ships that are not doing anything are wasting money.||Disband them or move them where they will be useful.

uiEntry.title: dy_navy-upkeep
uiEntry.tooltip: Amount of money per turn to support your fleets.||Disband ships to reduce this figure.||Fleets are made up of ships.||Each ship has an upkeep cost in its ship details panel.||Ships that are not doing anything are wasting money.||Disband them or move them where they will be useful.

uiEntry.title: tx_policing
uiEntry.tooltip: Amount of money per turn to support your town watch.||To keep the peace, every castle town needs militia (or town watch) to enforce public order. This is known as repression.||Public order is kept by keeping your population happy and repressing any trouble.||The more unhappy a population, the more repression you will need.||Some castle towns will need less repression than others and you can disband some units to save money.||Public order details can be found in your castle town details panel.||From this you can judge how much repression is needed.

uiEntry.title: dy_policing
uiEntry.tooltip: Amount of money per turn to support your town watch.||To keep the peace, every castle town needs militia (or town watch) to enforce public order. This is known as repression.||Public order is kept by keeping your population happy and repressing any trouble.||The more unhappy a population, the more repression you will need.||Some castle towns will need less repression than others and you can disband some units to save money.||Public order details can be found in your castle town details panel.||From this you can judge how much repression is needed.

uiEntry.title: tx_income_annual
uiEntry.tooltip: This will be added to your treasury next turn.||This is calculated from your incomings and outgoings as detailed above.

uiEntry.title: dy_annual-income
uiEntry.tooltip: This will be added to your treasury next turn.||This is calculated from your incomings and outgoings as detailed above.

uiEntry.title: dy_sum_credit
uiEntry.tooltip: The total of your incomings.||Your upkeep costs will be deducted from this to create your total income for the next turn.||Your tax, trade and other incomes (as detailed above) make up this sum.

uiEntry.title: dy_sum_debit
uiEntry.tooltip: The total of your outgoings.||This will be taken from your incomings to create your total income for the next turn.||Your army, naval and town watch upkeep costs make up this total.
